import ipywidgets as widgets
from IPython.display import display, HTML

javascript_functions = {False: "hide()", True: "show()"}
button_descriptions  = {False: "Show code", True: "Hide code"}


def toggle_code(state):

    """
    Toggles the JavaScript show()/hide() function on the div.input element.
    """

    output_string = "<script>$(\"div.input\").{}</script>"
    output_args   = (javascript_functions[state],)
    output        = output_string.format(*output_args)

    display(HTML(output))


def button_action(value):

    """
    Calls the toggle_code function and updates the button description.
    """

    state = value.new

    toggle_code(state)

    value.owner.description = button_descriptions[state]


state = False
toggle_code(state)

button = widgets.ToggleButton(state, description = button_descriptions[state])
button.observe(button_action, "value")

display(button)

ToggleButton(value=False, description='Show code')

Python provides powerful data visualization libraries including Matplotlib, Seaborn, Mayavi and others. They are free but offer functionality comparable with expensive commercial software thats why they are increasingly popular not only with individual users but also at companies.

1. Colors in Visualization

One of the most important components in data visualization is to use color effectively to enhance the visualization. This the codes in visualization.

1.1. RGB Colors

Every color can be obtained by mixing the shades of red (R), green (G), and blue (B). These are called additive primary colors or just primary colors. The resulting color depends on the proportions of the primary colors in the mix. It is customary to define these proportions by an integer number between 0 and 255 for each primary color. So, the resulting color is a triplet of integers between 0 and 255.

Examples of primary colors are red = [255, 0, 0], green = [0, 255, 0], blue = [0, 0, 255]. When the R, G, and B values are the same, the result is a shade of grey. With [0, 0, 0] one obtains black, with [255, 255, 255] white.

1.2. Secondary Colors

We already know that by primary colors we mean colors where only one of the R, G, B components is nonzero. Analogously, secondary colors are colors where only two of the R, G, B components are nonzero. The following figure shows the three most well-known secondary colors cyan, pink and yellow along with their RGB codes.

Keep in mind that the two nonzero components do not have to be the same. For instance, the colors [0, 214, 138], [50, 0, 100] and [145, 189, 0] are also secondary.

1.3. RGB Color Palettes

Sometimes one needs to find the right color for a specific application. In this case, it may be useful to browse some RGB palettes. In order to find them, search for "RGB color palette". There will be many results similar to each other, as shown in the following figure. [click the figure, it will bring you to a web site with interactive RGB color palettes]

2. Basics of Matplotlib

Matplotlib is a powerful Python visualization library originally written by John D. Hunter, an American neurobiologist. The library is fully compatible with Numpy and other Python libraries. It is customary to import it by typing import matplotlib.pyplot as plt.

The plot() function takes two arrays: x-coordinates and y-coordinates of points in the xy plane. Between the points, the curve is interpolated linearly.

Before we make actual Python plot, we

2.1. A "Hello World" Example of Python Plot

Let us illustrate this on a simple example with just five points [0, 0], [1, 2], [2, 0.5], [3, 2.5] and [4, 0]

In [70]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
x = [0.0, 1.0, 2.0, 3.0, 4.0]
y = [0.0, 2.0, 0.5, 2.5, 0.0]
## plot
plt.clf()       # clear plot in the existing graphic the new plot
plt.plot(x, y)  # plot the line-plot
plt.scatter(x, y, edgecolors='darkred', c='gold', s = 40)
## annotations
plt.xlabel("Horizontal Axis")
plt.ylabel("Vertical Axis")
plt.title("This is my first Python plot", c = "blue")
## caption
txt="Figure 1. My first plot in Python."
plt.figtext(0.5, -0.05, txt, wrap=False, horizontalalignment='center', fontsize=12, c = "red") 
plt.show()

The commands plt.clf(), plt.plot() and plt.show() do clear the canvas, plot the graph, and display the image, respectively.

Note: Don't be confused with plt.close and plt.clf()

plt.close() - It altogether plots the graph in seperate windows, releasing memory, retaining each window for view.

plt.clf() - It displays the graph in the same window one after other.

We cannot see the difference in the presentation, it is the way how Python manages the use of the memory internally.

2.2. Plotting Functions of One Variable

As an example, we plot the function f(x)=sin(x)f(x)=sin(x) in the interval (0,2)(0,2). The array of x-coordinates of equidistant points btween 0 and can be created easily using Numpys function linspace().

Line style can also be set separately using the optional parameter linestyle (or just ls) of the function plt.plot(). This parameter can have the values solid, dashed, dashdot, dotted, -, , -., and :.

In [98]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
##
x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 101)    # patterned sequence
y = np.sin(x)                       # evaluated patterned sequence with sin() in Numpy.
## plot the curve
plt.clf()
plt.plot(x, y, lw = 2, color = "darkred")
plt.plot([-0.3, 6.5],[0, 0], 'b--', label = "y = 0")

## title, caption and labels
plt.title("Sine Curve: " + r"$y=sin(x), x\in (0, \pi)$", color = "darkred", fontsize = 12)  
plt.xlabel(r"$x \in (0, \pi)$")  # r means the string will be treated as raw string.
plt.ylabel(r"$y \in [-1, 1]$")
plt.text(1.5, -1.65, "Figure 2: Sine curve:" + r"$x \in [0, \pi]$", color = "blue")
## legend
plt.legend(["sine curve", "x-axis"], loc ="lower left")
## show the curve
plt.show()

2.3. Figure Limits and Other Parameters

We can add more features to a plot to make it more effective.

In [105]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
##
x = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 101)    # patterned sequence
y = np.sin(x)                       # evaluated patterned sequence with sin() in Numpy.
## plot the curve
plt.clf()
plt.plot(x, y, lw = 2, color = "darkred")
plt.plot([-0.3, 6.5],[0, 0], 'b--', label = "y = 0")
## adjusting axes
plt.xlim(0, 2*np.pi)
plt.ylim(-1.5, 1.5)
## title, caption and labels
plt.title("Sine Curve: " + r"$y=sin(x), x\in (0, \pi)$", color = "darkred", fontsize = 12)  
plt.xlabel(r"$x \in (0, \pi)$")  # r means the string will be treated as raw string.
plt.ylabel(r"$y \in [-1, 1]$")
plt.text(1.5, -2.2, "Figure 2: Sine curve:" + r"$x \in [0, \pi]$", color = "blue")
## legend
plt.legend(["sine curve", "x-axis"], loc ="lower left")
## add grid to the plot
plt.grid()

## show the curve
plt.show()

3. 3D Plots

In [ ]:
### 3.1.

The Matplotlibs mplot3d toolkit provides several ways to plot graphs of functions of two variables.

f(x,y)=sin(x)sin(y)f(x,y)=sin(x)sin(y)

(x,y)(,)(,)(x,y)(,)(,).

3.1. Wireframe Plot

In [128]:
# Import Numpy and Matplotlib:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import axes3d

# Define intervals on the x and y axes and divisions:
x = np.linspace(-3, 3, 31)
y = np.linspace(-3, 3, 31)

# Create Cartesian grid:
X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)    # coordinates of the grid points
# Calculate values at grid points:
Z = np.sin(X) * np.sin(Y)   # The value of f(x,y) at each grid point (X,Y)
# Create 3D axes and plot the data:
fig = plt.figure(num=1, clear=True)  # this creates a figure object.
##
axes = plt.axes(projection = '3d')
axes.plot_wireframe(X, Y, Z, rstride = 1, cstride = 1, linewidth = 1, color='maroon')
axes.set_title('3D Plot:' + r'$f(x,y) = sin(x)sin(y)$', color = 'maroon') 
# Show the plot:
plt.show()
## save the figure
fig.savefig('./image/matplotlib-3d.png')  # save the figure to a subfolder in the current directory

Comments on Some Graphic Parameters

  • The purpose of using plt.figure() is to create a figure object. The whole figure is regarded as the figure object. It is necessary to explicitly use plt.figure() when we want to tweak the size of the figure and when we want to add multiple Axes objects in a single figure.

  • The parameters rstride (row stride) and cstride (column stride) can be used to make the plot coarser when they are set to 2, 3, etc.

3.2. Surface Plots and Color Maps

Function plot_surface accepts an optional parameter cmap ("color map").

In [139]:
# Import Numpy and Matplotlib:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import axes3d

# Define intervals on the x and y axes and divisions:
x = np.linspace(-3, 3, 31)
y = np.linspace(-3, 3, 31)

# Create Cartesian grid:

# Calculate values at grid points:

There are many color maps avaialble for surface plot. See https://matplotlib.org/stable/tutorials/colors/colormaps.html for more details.

Sometimes the default view is not optimal, in which case one can change the elevation and azimuthal angles via the function view_init. By elevation angle we mean the angle between the X-Y plane and the line connecting the camera and the origin [0, 0, 0]. By azimuthal angle, we mean the angle of rotation about the Z axis. With axes defined as in the above code, calling

5. Some Statistics Graphics

In this section, we will give some examples of statistical graphics.

5.1. Pie Chart

Matplotlibs pie charts are an elegant way to report the breakdown of an ensemble into parts. It provides the function pie for that.

In [167]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

data = [450, 550, 300]
labels = ['cats', 'dogs', 'mice']
plt.clf()
plt.axis('equal')
plt.pie(data, labels=labels)
plt.show()

A little fancier pie plot.

In [178]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

data = [450, 550, 300]
labels = ['cats', 'dogs', 'mice']
myexplode = [0, 0, 0.1, ]
##
plt.clf()
plt.axis('equal')
plt.pie(data, labels=labels, 
        explode = myexplode, 
        autopct= '%1.1f%%' , 
        shadow = True)
plt.legend(title = "Three Animals:")
plt.title('Exploded Pie Chart', color = 'maroon') 
##
plt.show()

5.2. Donut Charts

A special case of the pie chart is the "donut chart" which has a white circle inserted at the center. This time we will also show you how to use custom colors and how to rotate the pie chart.

The main things are self-explanatory. Hexadecimal RGB color codes have been discussed in Section 1.

In [179]:
# Import Matplotlib:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
labels = ['TVs', 'Monitors', 'Cameras', 'Printers', 'Scanners']
fractions = [15, 30, 5, 40, 10]
# Custom colors:
colors = ['#ff9999','#66b3ff','#99ff99','#ffcc99','#e6e6fa']
explode = (0, 0, 0, 0, 0) # No explode this time.
# Create the pie chart:
plt.clf()
plt.pie(fractions, colors=colors, labels=labels,
        autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=130,
        pctdistance=0.85, explode=explode)
# Draw a white circle at the center:
center_circle = plt.Circle((0, 0), 0.70, facecolor='white')
plt.gcf().gca().add_artist(center_circle)
# Display the pie chart:
plt.axis('equal')
plt.title('Donut Plot', color = 'maroon') 
plt.show()

Next we present a more advanced and meaningful bar chart that shows grouped comparisons.

In [191]:
# importing package
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
  
# create data
x = np.arange(5)
y1 = [34, 56, 12, 89, 67]
y2 = [12, 56, 78, 45, 90]
y3 = [14, 23, 45, 25, 89]
width = 0.2
  
# plot data in grouped manner of bar type
plt.bar(x-0.2, y1, width, color='cyan')
plt.bar(x, y2, width, color='orange')
plt.bar(x+0.2, y3, width, color='green')
plt.xticks(x, ['Team A', 'Team B', 'Team C', 'Team D', 'Team E'])
plt.xlabel("Teams")
plt.ylabel("Scores")
plt.title("Grouped Bar Chart")
plt.legend(["Round 1", "Round 2", "Round 3"])
plt.show()
